from various generations who navigated cultural difference. These stories reveal the critical importance of networks in coping with experiences of racism and establishing a successful life on the Prairies. This book offers an incisive look at the organizations, relationships, and ties that were critical in forging and sustaining life – yet it also serves as a remarkable record of the voices of some of the Prairies' most resilient and resourceful pioneers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChinesezPrairie ProvincesxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantszPrairie ProvincesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPioneerszPrairie ProvincesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311141999240uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482802440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774828024423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774828024/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-141999-2  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles